In a recent episode of the podcast â20VC with Harry Stebbings,â Salesforce founder and CEO Marc Benioff revealed that the company will stop hiring new software engineers by 2025. This decision is primarily due to the significant productivity boost of over 30% achieved by the engineering team through its flagship AI product, Agentforce, and other AI technologies.

He mentioned that although the demand for engineers has decreased, the efficiency of the engineering team has significantly improved due to the application of AI technologies, resulting in incredible work speed. Furthermore, he noted that there will be a reduction in support engineers next year, while the number of sales personnel will increase, as the company needs more sales teams to communicate the value of AI to customers.

Although Benioff mentioned that Salesforce might expand over the next five years, employees remain uneasy about the possibility of repeating the layoffs of the past two years in 2025. With the rapid advancement of AI technology, it remains to be seen what the future holds for Salesforce employees amid this transformation.

Watches evolved from ancient timekeeping devices. The earliest forms were sundials and water clocks, used by various civilizations to measure time based on the sunâs position or water flow. 

In the 13th century, mechanical clocks began to appear in Europe, powered by weights and gears. These early clocks were large, often placed in towers, and were mainly for public use. The first portable timepieces emerged in the late 15th century, known as "watches," which were typically carried in pockets.

By the 16th century, advancements in clockmaking led to smaller, more accurate watches. The introduction of the mainspring allowed for the compact design we recognize today. In the 17th century, innovations such as the balance spring improved accuracy significantly.

The 19th century saw mass production of watches, making them more accessible. This era also introduced wristwatches, initially worn by women, while men primarily used pocket watches. The shift to wristwatches gained momentum during World W*r 1, as they proved more practical for soldiers.

In the 20th century, quartz technology revolutionized watchmaking, offering even greater precision. Today, watches blend traditional craftsmanship with modern technology, including smart features and digital displays.
